                    Content = @"<h2>Criteria[<a href=\""https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Natural_science&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\"" title=\""Edit section: Criteria\"">edit</a>]</h2>

                    <p>Main article:&nbsp;<a href=\""https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy_of_science\"" title=\""Philosophy of science\"">Philosophy of science</a></p>

                    <p>Philosophers of science have suggested a number of criteria, including&nbsp;<a href=\""https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Popper\"" title=\""Karl Popper\"">Karl Popper</a>&#39;s controversial&nbsp;<a href=\""https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falsifiability\"" title=\""Falsifiability\"">falsifiability</a>&nbsp;criterion, to help them differentiate scientific endeavors from non-scientific ones.&nbsp;<a href=\""https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Validity_(statistics)\"" title=\""Validity (statistics)\"">Validity</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\""https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accuracy\"" title=\""Accuracy\"">accuracy</a>, and&nbsp;<a href=\""https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quality_control\"" title=\""Quality control\"">quality control</a>, such as&nbsp;<a href=\""https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peer_review\"" title=\""Peer review\"">peer review</a>&nbsp;and repeatability of findings, are amongst the most respected criteria in the present-day global scientific community.</p>

